ce:section.ce:para:
HCV RNA extraction was performed as follows: 150 μL serum was mixed with 50 μL of proteinase-K (20 mg/ml), then 300 μl of lysis/binding buffer (0.1 M Tris-HCl, pH 8.0, 0.5 M LiCl, 10 mM EDTA, pH 8, 1 % SDS, 5 mM DTT
) was added, and the mixture was incubated at room temperature for 10 min under roller shaking. Next, 200 μl of isopropanol was added to the mixture, and mixed well. Then, 2 mg of MBs/SiO2/HCV probe, was added, mixed well by pipetting heated at 75 °C for 3 min, and then incubated on the roller for 10 min. The MBs were then collected by a magnet and washed twice with washing buffer1 ( 10 mM Tris-HCl, pH 8.0, 0.15 M LiCl, 1 mM EDTA, 0.1 % SDS
) and washing buffer2 ( 10 mM Tris-HCl pH 8.0, 0.15 LiCl, 1 mM EDTA
). Washing with two washing buffers is necessary to eliminate the impurities, such as unbound RNA, non-specifically bound RNAs, and any remaining polysaccharides. The use of SDS in the first washing buffer ensures the removal of these impurities, thereby enhancing the purity of the sample for the downstream applications. The supernatant was removed, and the pellet was dried completely at room temperature for 15 min. Finally, 60 μL of RNAse-free water was added and heated for 3 min at 75 °C. The supernatant collected contains the HCV RNA. The pooled four negative samples control and all the negative samples were subjected to extraction following the above-mentioned protocol.
